title="Left ideal of a ring">left ideal</fr:link> and a <fr:link
type="local"
href="ra-0010.xml"
addr="ra-0010"
title="Right ideal of a ring">right ideal</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Furthermore, when <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\neq  R]]></fr:tex> we say <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is a <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Proper (two-sided) ideal</html:dfn> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>Some authors use the notation <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\trianglelefteq }R]]></fr:tex> to indicate <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex> is an ideal of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, as well as <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I\mathrel {\triangleleft }R]]></fr:tex> for proper ideals, analogous to the notation used for <fr:link
type="local"
href="gr-002P.xml"
addr="gr-002P"
title="Normal subgroup">Normal subgroup</fr:link>s.</fr:p>
 
   
