href="ra-000Q.xml"
addr="ra-000Q"
title="Subring">Subring</fr:link> of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>, same for one-sided ideals of <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[R]]></fr:tex>.</fr:p>
<fr:p>(4) Traditionally, the historic notation used to indicate we're working with ideals was to use fraktur letters (<fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {a}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {b}]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathfrak {c}]]></fr:tex>, and so on). This was a horrible decision. Modern conventions use <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[I]]></fr:tex>, <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[J]]></fr:tex>, and variants using apostrophes or indices.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter><fr:backmatter /></fr:tree>
 
