type="local"
href="hungerford-1974-algebra.xml"
addr="hungerford-1974-algebra"
title="Algebra">Algebra</fr:link> Theorem 1.6.13</fr:meta></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Let <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[n\in \mathbb {N}]]></fr:tex> be a positive integer. We define the <html:dfn
xmlns:html="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">Dihedral group</html:dfn> <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[D_{n}]]></fr:tex> to consist of the set <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[\{x^{k}y^{j}\mid  0\leq  k<n,0\leq  j\leq  1\}]]></fr:tex> where we also write <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[x^{0}y^{0}=1]]></fr:tex>, such that
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[x^{n}=y^{2}=1]]></fr:tex>
and also
<fr:tex
display="block"><![CDATA[yx=x^{-1}y.]]></fr:tex>
It's not hard to see <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[yx^{k}=x^{-k}y]]></fr:tex> by applying that second relation <fr:tex
display="inline"><![CDATA[k]]></fr:tex> times.</fr:p>
 
   
